NOROVIRUS, BADMINTON TOURNAMENT - NEW ZEALAND (SOUTH ISLAND)
************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>
[1]
Date: Tue 10 Apr 2007
From: Joseph Dudley <fnjpd@uaf.edu>
Source: The New Zealand Herald [edited]
<http://www.nzherald.co.nz/section/1/story.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=10433428>

Badminton officials have suspended play for 24 hours at an
international tournament in Christchurch (New Zealand) after a
stomach bug cut a swathe through a large number of competitors.
Since Sat 7 Apr 2007, more than 80 people at the trans-Tasman
under-17 tournament, players, coaches, and tournament officials, have
succumbed to a bug causing vomiting and diarrhea. Public health
officials called in to try to identify the source of the outbreak met
tournament officials this afternoon [10 Apr 2007] after diagnosing
the gut-wrenching stomach bug, norovirus, as the most likely cause.
Canterbury medical officer of health, Alistair Humphrey, said tonight
[10 Apr 2007] a 2nd wave of infection that hit tournament
participants overnight was "characteristic of a norovirus infection".
Highly infectious norovirus causes vomiting and diarrhea. It is
spread through contact with infected people, and contaminated food
and eating surfaces.
Generally it is present in the community in various strains and
outbreaks are periodically linked to institutions, such as hospitals
and rest homes, and where people are confined in close contact with
each other. Wards in hospitals in Christchurch and Dunedin have been
closed in 2007 through norovirus outbreaks.
Dr Humphrey told NZPA (New Zealand Press Association) a shared dinner
during the June Bevan Badminton Trophy tournament opening ceremonies
on Friday [6 Apr 2007] was the "prime suspect" as the infection's source.
While norovirus was not primarily a foodborne infection, it was
likely something happened at that event where an infected person
passed on the infection to many others.
"We are questioning the caterers and we will be analyzing all the
data collected from questionnaires from the tournament participants
to see if there's any common link between them all," Dr Humphrey said.
About 74 people had been affected in the 1st wave of norovirus on Sat
and Sun, 7-8 Apr 2007. A further 12 had become ill last night [9 Apr
2007], he said.
Tournament organisers had decided this afternoon [10 Apr 2007] to
halt the competition for 24 hours to allow those affected to fully recover.
"It's not spread beyond the tournament, but the officials running the
competition felt that, given they had enough time, they would rather
suspend competition for 24 hours to help break the chain of
infection," Dr Humphrey said.
Public health officials had contacted counterparts in Australia where
several norovirus outbreaks had been reported at sporting events, and
would continue to monitor the current situation here. Most of those
affected in the 1st wave were recovering well, he said.
