[2]
Date: Tue 10 Apr 2007
From: Brent Barrett <salbrent@sbcglobal.net>
Source: Radio New Zealand News [edited]
<http://www.radionz.co.nz/news/latest/200704100813/tournament_resumes_after_stomach_bug_outbreak>

An international badminton tournament in Christchurch will resume on
Tue 10 Apr 2007, after a third of those taking part were laid low
with gastroenteritis.
Altogether, 180 players from clubs throughout New Zealand and
Australia are competing in the trans-Tasman under-17 tournament. The
illness, which causes diarrhea and vomiting, has affected 60 people
including players, coaches and officials.
Canterbury Medical Officer of Health, Alistair Humphrey, says an
investigation is under way to find the source of the illness. Those
suffering symptoms are filling in questionnaires about where they
have been and what they have eaten, in an effort to work out whether
the disease is food poisoning or a virus.
Tournament organizer, Lyndsay Dick, told Morning Report that it is
too early to tell if the illness was the result of a shared meal on
Friday night, 6 Apr 2007. Ms Dick says the symptoms of
gastroenteritis are short-lived, and the tournament can go ahead.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[The illness here may well be norovirus but a variety of short-lived
foodborne pathogens or toxins could be involved. Not enough
information has been given to better assess possible etiologies.
Badminton (<http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Badminton>) is a racket
sport played by either 2 opposing players (singles) or opposing pairs
(doubles), who take positions on opposite halves of a rectangular
court divided by a net. Players score points by striking a
shuttlecock with their rackets so that it passes over the net and
lands in their opponents' half of the court. The shuttlecock is a
feathered projectile whose unique aerodynamic properties cause it to
fly differently from the balls used in most racket sports; in
particular, the feathers create much higher drag, causing the
shuttlecock to decelerate more rapidly than a ball. Because
shuttlecock flight is strongly affected by wind, competitive
badminton is always played indoors. Badminton is also played outdoors
as a casual recreational activity, often as a garden or beach game.
A map of New Zealand showing Christchurch on the country's South
Island can be found at
<http://www.lonelyplanet.com/mapshells/australasia/new_zealand/new_zealand.htm>.
- Mod.LL]
